@*
    Basic — default rendering (icon button + listbox).

    The simplest possible mount. Each option renders with its locale's
    pretty name (from the built-in `locales.tsv` table), carrying a
    `lang="…"` attribute so screen readers pronounce each in the right
    language.

    Outcome: a globe icon button that opens a listbox of three options.
    Picking one writes <html lang="…" dir="…">, closes the listbox,
    returns focus to the button, and updates the bindable Value.

    The status line is part of the pattern, not an extra. The closed
    control is an icon button showing only the globe glyph, never the
    active locale name — so without this line a sighted user has no way
    to read the current selection off the control. (A screen-reader user
    can: reopening the listbox announces the active option as
    aria-selected.) See docs/accessibility.md.

    aria-live="polite" announces mutations only, so this stays silent on
    first paint and speaks once on each subsequent change — exactly what
    a locale switch warrants (it is not an interruption).

    It is rendered visible on purpose: sighted users need the selection
    echoed too, and visible text helps cognitive accessibility. If a
    design genuinely cannot spare the space, keep the element and hide it
    with a visually-hidden (sr-only) class rather than deleting it.

    The locale's own name carries its own `lang`, for the same WCAG 3.1.2
    (Language of Parts) reason the options do — so "Français" is spoken
    with a French voice inside this English sentence.
*@

@page "/examples/locale-chooser/radios"
@rendermode InteractiveServer
@using LilyDesignSystem.Blazor.Helpers

<LocaleChooser
    Label="Choose your language"
    Locales="@(new[] { "en", "fr", "ar" })"
    @bind-Value="locale" />

<p class="locale-chooser-status" aria-live="polite">
    Active language:
    <span lang="@Locales.Bcp47LocaleTag(locale)">@Locales.LocaleName(locale)</span>
</p>

@code {
    private string locale = "en";
}
